{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"coaching":[],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":0,"blocking":0,"dropped":0,"indeterminate":18},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","probed":1,"ran":true,"references":1,"resolved":1,"status":"pass","unresolved_or_abstained":0},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":4522,"file_impact":1,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"pass","verify_commands_linted":45,"verify_lint_abstained":45},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":1152,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":1,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":313.8,"llm_calls":29,"llm_ms":393957.2,"total_ms":394385.1,"verify_requests":19},"remediation":{"baseline":"signature","eligible":false,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":false,"plan_changed":true,"prior_sidecar":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"signed":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","F4","G5","T12","T2","T4","T5b","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Anchor the `.authorship.signed` assertion with a concrete expected value (e.g. `jq -e '.authorship.signed == true'` or `jq -e '.authorship.signed | length >= 1'`) so the check is unambiguous.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"evidenced by a new event on a work ticket whose `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` increased\"","Defect taxonomy item (5): missing cardinality assertion; item (6): prose-vs-structured assertion target — no concrete expected value anchored."],"finding":"The supplementary signing check `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` with the qualifier 'increased' has no concrete assertion value stated — the plan does not specify whether `.authorship.signed` is a boolean (assert `== true`), a signature count (assert `-gt 0`), or another type, making the check unexecutable as written.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff8177cfb3d1c393f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, step (a): 'rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed' increased'","norm_id":"n0586455522627463","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An executor runs the command and sees some output but does not know what value constitutes 'increased' (true vs false, 0 vs 1, an array length).","If `.authorship.signed` is a boolean, 'increased' is meaningless — the assertion silently passes or fails depending on interpretation."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace 'increased' with a concrete jq assertion: `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed == true'` (if boolean) or `rebar show <t> | jq -e '(.authorship.signed | length) >= 1'` (if an array of sigs). State which schema applies.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Define the canary write fallback: name the mechanism (e.g. a specific workflow input or step), the trigger command, and the proving command showing the canary event is signed and verified, or remove the reference if the primary retrigger path is sufficient.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E2","E6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id, not merely a green run\"","The canary write mechanism is not described anywhere else in the plan; no trigger command, expected output, or proving command is given for it."],"finding":"The plan introduces 'use the workflow's own canary write' as an alternative path when no Jira delta exists, but does not define what the canary write is, how to trigger it, or how to verify its signed output — leaving the fallback path unexecutable.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4f6c8c53b686a281","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 're-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write'","norm_id":"nc7659db1ac66d4d4","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An executor triggers multiple runs with no Jira delta and decides to use the canary path, but has no spec for what that means or how to verify it produces a signed event.","The canary path may not exist or may not produce a verifiable signed ticket event — an executor cannot confirm this without external knowledge."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Reconcile the canary-write fallback with AC2: either extend AC2 to explicitly accept a canary event (naming the verify command for that event type) or remove the canary fallback from 'What' and require a real work-ticket event.","cohort":["COH","E1","T4"],"criteria":["COH","E1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'What': 're-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id'","AC2: 'a new event on a work ticket whose rebar show <t> | jq \\'.authorship.signed\\' increased'","Canary write is described as a fallback equivalent in 'What' but AC2's verify step is scoped to work tickets, not canary events"],"finding":"The 'What' body offers 'the workflow's own canary write' as a fallback path to satisfy the AC when no Jira delta is available, but AC2's verify step requires 'a new event on a work ticket' — a canary write may not be a work-ticket event and would not satisfy AC2 as written.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f17df39d50377f39b","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"'What' section (last paragraph) vs AC2 verify step","norm_id":"n559baf46a922be7b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A run triggers with no Jira delta; operator uses the canary write as evidence; AC2 cannot actually be verified because the canary event is not a work-ticket event and the jq command has nothing to run against."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In AC2, add a parenthetical: '(if no Jira delta is available, a canary write event satisfies this criterion; substitute the canary event id for <t> and confirm `rebar show <canary-event-id> | jq .authorship.signed` is non-null)'.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit rollback plan for the secret re-set: e.g., 'Before overwriting, confirm the SSM path and key fingerprint match the registered public key on identity 594c (`rebar show-identity 594c | jq .keys`); if the post-re-set run does not produce a verified event, restore from SSM by repeating the set step after re-verifying the SSM value.'","cohort":["COH","E1","T4"],"criteria":["T4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Precondition': 'Because a GitHub secret value cannot be read back, this story re-sets it from the authoritative SSM source'","If the SSM value is wrong or the wrong SSM path is read, the previous (potentially correct) secret value is gone and unrecoverable","No back-out or rollback step is described anywhere in the plan"],"finding":"The secret re-set is an irreversible overwrite of a GitHub write-only secret (the prior value is unrecoverable after overwrite), but the plan provides no explicit rollback or back-out path for the case where the SSM-sourced key proves incorrect or stale.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f608d4c96b43a86d5","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"'What' section — 'Re-set the REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY GitHub Actions secret'","norm_id":"n0cb819131dd51b3b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["The operator reads a stale or rotated SSM value, overwrites the working secret, signing breaks on subsequent CI runs, and there is no documented path to recover the pre-existing secret value."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a pre-condition check step: verify that the fingerprint of the SSM private key matches the public key registered on identity 594c before overwriting the GitHub secret. Document this as a guard against silent mis-set.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit rollback instruction: specify that `gh secret delete REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar` (or equivalent) restores the pre-story unsigned-advisory behavior, and document when to use it.","cohort":["T12","T5b","T9"],"criteria":["T12"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'if REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY is empty the materialize step logs \"writes will be unsigned (advisory)\" and exits 0' — only the empty-key path is documented as graceful","No rollback instruction appears anywhere in the plan","'No enforcement flip here (8d39)' confirms the plan is aware of scope, but rollback is not addressed"],"finding":"No rollback path is specified for the case where the newly populated secret holds an incorrect key (e.g., key mismatch between SSM and the public key registered on identity 594c). While the workflow gracefully falls back to unsigned writes on an empty secret, a non-empty but wrong key may produce a different failure mode not covered by the 'unsigned advisory' branch, and there is no explicit instruction to delete or clear the secret to restore the pre-story state.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f7bd13819755f5f1f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section / AC — 'Secret populated from SSM'","norm_id":"n0304d32955d2032b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["SSM holds a stale/rotated key not matching the public key registered on 594c; CI runs silently produce mis-attributed or error-state events; operator must discover and clear the secret but has no documented procedure"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Rollback' subsection under Scope: 'To undo: `gh secret delete REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar`; subsequent CI runs will revert to unsigned-advisory mode (exit 0, no enforcement impact until story 8d39 flips).'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Document the key-rotation maintenance procedure: when the SSM key at `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` is rotated, this story's `gh secret set` command must be re-run; link to ADR-0012 or a runbook entry so the dependency is not implicit.","cohort":["T12","T5b","T9"],"criteria":["T9"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says to re-set the secret 'from the authoritative SSM source' but only as a one-time act","No rotation schedule or trigger is mentioned","ADR-0012 is cited but its rotation policy is not surfaced in this plan"],"finding":"The lifecycle for key rotation is unspecified: when the Rebar Bot ed25519 key is rotated in SSM (ADR-0012), there is no documented procedure or trigger to re-set `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` in GitHub Actions. The secret will silently drift from the authoritative SSM value, producing the same class of bug this story was designed to prevent.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f79e25a9eb77eff99","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Precondition section / 'The private key is available from AWS SSM SecureString /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key (ADR-0012)'","norm_id":"n19f683d1515dd407","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Key is rotated in SSM for security hygiene; GitHub secret is not updated; CI continues using the old private key, which no longer matches the registered public key on identity 594c; signed events fail verification silently until the enforcement flip (8d39) exposes the break"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify the canary-write fallback: state explicitly that the workflow's canary write IS sufficient to satisfy the AC (naming the event type it produces and confirming it is authored by 594c), OR add a maximum retry count/time-box after which the canary write is the mandatory proof path.","cohort":["E3","F4","T6"],"criteria":["E3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'If a given run has no inbound Jira delta to translate (so it writes no work-ticket event), re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write'","The canary write is mentioned as a fallback but not described as guaranteed or specified: what event type it produces, whether it is always authored by 594c, and whether it counts as 'in-scope' for the AC are not stated."],"finding":"The AC's retry condition ('re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event') has no stated upper bound or timeout, leaving the acceptance criterion potentially open-ended. If no Jira delta arrives and the canary write path is not explicitly guaranteed to produce a signed event, the story could stall indefinitely.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fece33b22e71149be","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — second bullet; 'What' section paragraph 3","norm_id":"na923fbc5c646e0c7","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Operator triggers multiple runs, none produce Jira delta; canary write path is ambiguous; AC is never provably closed without additional clarification."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add one sentence to the AC: 'If no Jira delta arrives after N dispatches (suggested: 3), use the workflow canary write as the proof event; it is authored by 594c and counts as an in-scope signed event for this AC.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a one-sentence rationale in AC2 explaining why `--all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"` is the correct verification command (e.g. 'uses `--all` because it enforces every event the run introduced after anchor `$C`, matching the enforcement the future `require_authenticated` flip will apply, while `--since \"$C\"` grandfathers pre-existing unsigned events so the check is non-vacuous and attributable solely to the triggered run').","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan AC2: 'rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"' exits 0 (had the bot event been unsigned it would exit non-zero — this is exactly the enforcement the flip will apply)'","verify_authorship.py lines 505-510: --since makes events before the ref grandfathered (not enforced), but --all still scans the entire store — any unsigned event introduced by a concurrent actor after $C (e.g. a manual rebar write on the tickets branch) would cause exit 1 even if the bot's event is signed","The plan states no positive rationale for choosing --all over --base or a targeted single-event check"],"finding":"The AC2 verification command uses `--all` scope against the full store, but the plan never explains why `--all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"` is the right instrument (vs. a targeted per-event check or `--base`). Without this rationale, an operator could unknowingly substitute a narrower check that passes vacuously (e.g., `--base HEAD` on an already-ahead branch) or misinterpret a non-zero exit as a signing failure when it is actually a pre-existing unrelated unsigned event introduced after $C by a concurrent actor.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f55d4dcea221ca4a0","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, verification command `rebar verify-identity --all --require-authenticated --since \"$C\"`","norm_id":"n98511f9ba6ed40c9","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A concurrent `rebar` write to the tickets branch (e.g. a developer's local push) lands after $C but before the operator runs the verification; the command exits 1 not because of the bot's event but because of that unsigned event — the operator may misattribute the failure to the signing setup.","An operator substitutes `--base HEAD~1` thinking it's equivalent, but that checks the last local commit rather than all events since the run's anchor — potentially vacuous if the tickets branch had been rebased."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the AC2 text, after the `rebar verify-identity` command, add: '(`--all` enforces every event after anchor `$C`, matching future enforcement scope; `--since \"$C\"` grandfathers pre-existing unsigned events so the exit code is attributable solely to the events this run introduced.)'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] **[T10 Least-Privilege]** Specify the minimum IAM permissions (e.g., `ssm:GetParameter` + `kms:Decrypt` on the exact SSM ARN) and the AWS identity/role the operator should use to read `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key`, so key-material retrieval is not performed with over-privileged credentials.","cohort":["T10"],"criteria":["T10"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan says to feed the \"decrypted SSM value\" to `gh secret set` but gives no IAM access specification","ADR-0012 is referenced but its contents are not surfaced in the plan","No role ARN, permission boundary, or `aws sts assume-role` command is named"],"finding":"The plan invokes AWS SSM (`/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key`) to retrieve the private key but never specifies what IAM identity or role the operator must assume, nor the minimum permissions required (`ssm:GetParameter` on that specific ARN with KMS decrypt). Without this, an operator might use overly broad credentials (e.g., AdministratorAccess) by default, violating least-privilege.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f59eccfc4c3316d89","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Precondition section: \"The private key is available from AWS SSM SecureString `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` (ADR-0012)\"","norm_id":"n9d2090a985371b07","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Operator uses a personal AWS profile with broad permissions to read SSM, establishing a precedent of wide-scope credential use for key-material retrieval","A new operator following this plan cannot determine the minimum AWS permissions needed and escalates unnecessarily"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a one-line IAM note in the 'What' or 'Precondition' section: e.g., \"Retrieve via an IAM identity scoped to `ssm:GetParameter` on `arn:aws:ssm:REGION:ACCOUNT:parameter/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` and `kms:Decrypt` on its CMK — do not use AdministratorAccess or a role with broader SSM path wildcards.\"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] **[T10 Observability/Reproducibility]** Document (or codify) the secret-provisioning procedure as a durable, discoverable artifact — either a checked-in runbook (`docs/ops/rotate-rebar-bot-signing-key.md`) or a Terraform `github_actions_secret` resource — so the step is reproducible without ticket archaeology.","cohort":["T10"],"criteria":["T10"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states no repo file changes; the secret set command is a manual CLI invocation","No Terraform or other IaC resource managing `github_actions_secret` is mentioned","ADR-0012 is referenced for SSM but no equivalent governance artifact is cited for the GitHub secret itself"],"finding":"The GitHub Actions secret `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` is provisioned via a manual `gh secret set` CLI command and is not managed as-code (no Terraform `github_actions_secret` resource or equivalent). The plan explicitly declares `file_impact` empty and says no workflow YAML is modified, meaning there is no reproducible, auditable IaC artifact to re-create or rotate the secret. Recovery depends entirely on out-of-band institutional knowledge.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8b2ec9b3dbb0d2f8","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section: \"Empty `file_impact` is correct: no tracked repo file changes.\" / What section: \"`gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar`\"","norm_id":"n95ff637ef298da02","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Secret needs rotation 6 months later; the only record of how to re-populate it is buried in this ticket's comments","A new maintainer does not know the SSM source path or the correct `gh` invocation and cannot reproduce the provisioning step"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add the concrete AWS CLI retrieval command (`aws ssm get-parameter --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key --with-decryption --query Parameter.Value --output text`) and any required `AWS_REGION`/profile preconditions to the What section or AC1, so the operator step is fully reproducible from the plan.","cohort":["T3"],"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar fed the decrypted SSM value; never echoed'","Plan text: 'The private key is available from AWS SSM SecureString /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key (ADR-0012)'","No AWS CLI command, region, or IAM precondition is stated anywhere in the plan","Partially-verified: the SSM path and secret name are stated; the retrieval command and auth preconditions are absent"],"finding":"The plan describes the SSM retrieval step as 'fed the decrypted SSM value' (`gh secret set … fed the decrypted SSM value`) but never states the concrete AWS CLI command, the required AWS region, IAM role/profile, or `--with-decryption` flag needed to read the SecureString. An operator following the plan cannot complete the secret-population step without this information.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f41c8c2bd5d24b6e3","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section / AC1: 'Re-set the `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` GitHub Actions secret … fed the decrypted SSM value; never echoed'","norm_id":"nc78eb14dcd4060d2","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Operator runs `gh secret set` piped from `aws ssm get-parameter` but lacks the correct AWS region env var or IAM permissions — the step silently sets the wrong or empty value, downstream signing fails, and the AC is not satisfied."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the What section, expand the re-set step to: `aws ssm get-parameter --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key --with-decryption --query Parameter.Value --output text | gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar --body -` and note the required AWS region (e.g. `AWS_REGION=us-east-1` or whichever region hosts the parameter).","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Sharpen AC2 clause (a): replace `jq '.authorship.signed'` with a before-capture command (e.g. `BEFORE=$(rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed')`) run before the trigger, then assert `AFTER > BEFORE` after the run — or replace the counter check entirely with a per-event `author_sig` presence check (e.g. `rebar show <t> --format json | jq '.events[-1].author_sig != null'`) that directly proves the new event is signed rather than relying on an aggregate counter.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'a new event on a work ticket whose `rebar show <t> | jq '\\''`.authorship.signed'\\''` increased'","src/rebar/reducer/_state.py:53: `\"authorship\": {\"signed\": 0, \"unsigned\": 0}` — seeded as integer counters","src/rebar/reducer/_replay.py:205-207: `_bucket = \"signed\" if event.get(\"author_sig\") else \"unsigned\"` / `_counts[_bucket] = _counts.get(_bucket, 0) + 1` — confirms these are additive presence counts","The plan never states the expected before/after integer values, nor does it explain how to isolate the count delta introduced by the specific run being proved","ABSENCE: the plan does not provide a before-capture command for `.authorship.signed` analogous to the `C=$(git -C .tickets-tracker rev-parse HEAD)` anchor used for commit-level diffing"],"finding":"The AC references `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` and says its value 'increased', but the plan never defines the field's type or the concrete assertion value. Code inspection confirms `.authorship.signed` is an integer COUNTER (not a boolean), incremented by the reducer for every event carrying an `author_sig`. 'Increased' is ambiguous for a cumulative counter: if prior runs already wrote signed events to the same ticket, the counter could be >0 before the run, making a delta check impossible without capturing the before value; if no prior events exist, any nonzero value passes. An operator executing this AC cannot determine what assertion to make.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f69b9223564d1fb56","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, clause (a): `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` with qualifier 'increased'","norm_id":"nada747a7a58bec5b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Operator runs `rebar show <t> | jq '.authorship.signed'` and sees `3` after the run but doesn't know if it was `2` or `0` before — 'increased' is unfalsifiable without a baseline capture.","A ticket that already had 5 signed events from prior reconciler runs shows `6` after the new run — the field incremented, but the operator cannot confirm the new event specifically is signed without a per-event check.","A ticket with zero prior events shows `1` — this case is clear, but the AC doesn't say to target a freshly-created ticket, so the general case is ambiguous."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a before-capture step: `ASIGNED_BEFORE=$(rebar show <ticket_id> | jq '.authorship.signed')` immediately before triggering the run, then after the run assert `rebar show <ticket_id> | jq '.authorship.signed'` is greater than `$ASIGNED_BEFORE`. Alternatively, reference the per-event field directly: `rebar show <ticket_id> | jq '[.events[] | select(.uuid == \"<event_uuid>\") | .author_sig != null] | all'`.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The AC2 proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` passes the literal four-character string \"E\" as the jq variable `$u` (because `--arg u E` binds the text `E`, not the shell variable `$E`), so the check passes trivially for any run where no event has uuid literally \"E\" — the actual event uuid is never compared.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f551c0d14c9a959cd","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — second AC bullet, proving command","norm_id":"nb33e20504164983c","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace:\n```\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nWith (assuming the event uuid is stored in shell variable `$E`):\n```\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The AC2 jq proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` is mechanically broken: jq's `--arg name value` syntax passes the *literal string* 'value' to `$name`, so `--arg u E` sets `$u` to the four-character string 'E', not the shell variable `$E`. Because no real event uuid equals 'E', the filter `all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)` is a tautology (always true) and exits 0 even if the target event IS present in the non-verified report — producing a guaranteed false-green verification with no diagnostic value.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc708d1af1a1e690b","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria → AC2 proving command: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n6ec6daa86c49cae4","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Record the event uuid first: `E=<the uuid from rebar show <t>>`, then run: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`. The double-quoted shell expansion `\"$E\"` passes the variable's value as jq's argument string, not the literal character 'E'.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"AC2's absence-from-report proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` passes the literal four-character string `\"E\"` as jq's `$u` variable, not the shell variable holding the actual event UUID. jq's `--arg name value` syntax takes two positional words: `name=u`, `value=E` (the letter). Any real event UUID (e.g. `abc1-...`) trivially satisfies `!= 'E'`, so the command exits 0 regardless of whether the target event is verified — the proof is vacuously true.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdcaaca7dac96a75f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n36e7e86c55aae57b","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace the command with: `E=<recorded-event-uuid>; rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The jq proving command in AC2 passes the literal string 'E' as the jq variable value rather than the shell variable's content: `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` assigns $u = \"E\" (the letter), so the assertion checks that no event has uuid == 'E', which is always true and proves nothing. The correct form requires quoting the shell variable: `--arg u \"$E\"`.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc6568c0e21b76f1e","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — second AC bullet, proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"nd811bbbfe0f46f69","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"```bash\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json \\\n  | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nAlternatively, for a more direct positive proof, add: `rebar verify-identity \"$E\"` (or equivalent) and assert exit 0.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The AC2 proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` is mechanically broken: jq's `--arg name value` syntax binds the literal token `E` (a four-character string) to `$u`, not the shell variable holding the actual event UUID. Because no real UUID equals the string \"E\", the `all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)` predicate trivially returns true and exits 0 for every possible input — it is a permanently vacuous check that cannot detect the case where event E actually does appear in the non-verified report.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f80d887127cd08701","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, second bullet: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n235f9264c3c6942f","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Replace the proving command with:\n```sh\nE=\"<the recorded event uuid>\"\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nThe double-quoted `\"$E\"` causes the shell to expand the variable before passing its value to jq's `--arg` parser.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G7"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The parent epic (dc09) specifies story 2 as confirming that both 'reconcile-bridge (and its canary)' produce signed events on a real run. The leaf's ACs only require a reconcile-bridge run to produce a signed event; no AC independently requires the canary workflow to produce a separately confirmed, verified signed event.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"faeac75fcd81073b2","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Leaf Acceptance Criteria (AC2) vs. dc09 'Scope / planned child stories' item 2","norm_id":"nf5e54b113ae70adc","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":[],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to AC2 (or as a separate AC): '[operator-attested] A `reconcile-bridge-canary` run produces ≥1 event authored by `594c`, confirmed verified via `rebar verify-identity --all --format json`; the workflow-run URL and signed event uuid are recorded on this ticket.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"dcde7c38eece81b0","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":313.8,"llm_calls":29,"llm_ms":393957.2,"total_ms":394385.1,"verify_requests":19},"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","regver":"b293b9a55de591cc","runner":"pydantic_ai","schema":"plan_review_result_v2","ticket_id":"4dc0-d003-c236-45de","ticket_type":"story","verdict":"INDETERMINATE","verified_at_sha":"6b25dbead186639a436b1d5faf7cb03e99001efc"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"REVIEW_RESULT","timestamp":1784239202454464001,"uuid":"3dac64a2-575d-44eb-b4fc-8e03e9d055c4"}